HTML naming convention follows BEM with type descriptors based on
https://csswizardry.com/2015/03/more-transparent-ui-code-with-namespaces/

o-- object = element that is repeated in multiple contexts (e.g. buttons, tags, ...)
c-- component = element that is used in one specific context
u-- modifier = class that is used as utility; e.g. components/objects that can require another element, but not of a specific type; e.g. filters
is--, has-- = specific modifier for an element that is in a specific state
js-- JavaScript hook

example: A gallery filled with images
<div class="o--gallery"> //the gallery block
    <div class="o--gallery-item"> //an item in the gallery can also be put into other contexts, thus they are object o-- by themselves
        <div class="c--gallery-item__media"> //the media block is a wrapper, thus l-- for an image or a video or other media
            <img class="c--gallery-item__image o--centered-image"> //the image itself is a component, thus c--; It can also use aa common image layout, which makes its layout a reusable object, thus o--image-centered
        </div>
        <div class="c--gallery-item__caption"> //the caption is a wrapper for the title and description, thus l--
            <h1 class="c--gallery-item__title"> a title </h1> //component, could also use a general layout o--
            <p class="c--gallery-item__description"> a description </p> //component, could also use a general layout o--
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="o--gallery-item">
        ...
    </div>
    ...
</div>